            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kian Rostami\u2019s story began not in San Francisco, but in the warm, suburban sprawl of San Jose, where his parents landed after leaving Tehran in the late 1980s. An engineer father and a linguist mother instilled in him a deep respect for both precision and poetry, a duality that would come to define his life. They envisioned a stable future for their son in medicine or tech, the well-trodden paths of successful immigrant children.\n\nKian, however, found his calling in the quiet galleries of the San Jose Museum of Art. During his undergraduate years at UC Davis, a part-time job installing student shows revealed his true talent: he was a natural at organization, a born facilitator who could translate an artist's chaotic vision into a seamless public experience. This was his turning point. Choosing a graduate degree in Arts Administration was an act of quiet rebellion, a declaration that he would build his own bridge between the creative and the practical.\n\nNow, at 31, Kian is the Exhibitions Manager for a prominent SoMa gallery. He thrives on the controlled chaos of his work\u2014juggling budgets, managing artists, and overseeing the complex logistics of transforming an empty white space into a world of compelling ideas. His days are a flurry of emails and consultations, but his proudest moments are in the silent hours before an opening, when the lights are perfect and the art finally speaks for itself.\n\nHis life is contained within a few vibrant miles of the city. He lives in a clean, minimalist apartment in the Mission District, a neighborhood whose layered history and artistic energy resonate with him. His daily 2.5-mile bike commute is a cherished ritual, a mental transition from the colorful murals of his street to the polished floors of the gallery. His social life revolves around a tight-knit circle of friends\u2014a mix of fellow arts professionals and tech workers who appreciate his grounded perspective.\n\nKian\u2019s greatest aspiration is to curate a major exhibition of contemporary Iranian-American artists, a project that would finally synthesize the two halves of his identity. He envisions a show that speaks to the diaspora experience, honoring the heritage his parents gave him while celebrating the unique path he has carved for himself in the heart of San Francisco."
